The paper deals with the computational complexity of the Densest $k$-Subgraph problem, which is a fundamental problem in computer science related to graph theory. The paper uses techniques from computational complexity theory, information theory, and graph theory to prove a lower bound on the running time of algorithms for this problem. Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Additionally, the paper also involves combinatorial and graph-theoretic arguments, which suggest the sub-categories cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory). Finally, the paper uses information-theoretic machinery, which suggests the sub-category cs.IT (Information Theory).
